{
  "artifact": "qurl-agent-assignment-golden-vectors",
  "schema_version": 1,
  "description": "Deterministic NHP hub-to-cell enrollment packets for initial and refreshed assignment, assigned-cell REG activation with an opaque one-shot ticket, and assigned-cell registration completion with an SDK-generated persisted device API-key candidate; plus strict request-rejection cases and the closed v1 application-error taxonomy.",
  "source_of_truth": "github.com/layervai/qurl-conformance",
  "notes": [
    "Every success-path request and result is DETERMINISTIC. A conformant implementation MUST reproduce packet_hex byte-for-byte from the named sender/receiver keys, fixed ephemeral_priv_hex, timestamp_nanos, counter, preamble_hex, and the exact UTF-8 bytes in body_json. body_hex is those same body_json bytes encoded as lowercase hex.",
    "NHP_LST is header type 5, NHP_LRT is type 6, NHP_REG is type 13, and NHP_RAK is type 14. Every result counter exactly echoes its request counter. LST/LRT never uses NHP_COK; pre-handler overload shedding appears as a timeout governed only by the SDK's bounded transaction retry.",
    "initial_assignment and refresh_assignment target the bootstrap hub. The initial hub request presents the unregistered agent public key at the Noise layer and a credential in usrData; the hub plugin hashes and validates that credential and derives owner identity rather than trusting usrId. Supporting that request requires the hub endpoint's deliberate unregistered-LST validation posture.",
    "The initial assignment result alone supplies registration metadata and an opaque short-lived assignment_ticket. assigned_cell_registration carries that exact ticket in REG usrData and targets the public key returned by assignment. The server consumes the ticket one-shot in the atomic registration activation transaction. Ordinary refresh returns only the sticky assignment/binding and never issues a registration ticket.",
    "The bootstrap/preissued success path registers directly with NHP_REG and does not send NHP_OTP. Optional account-enrollment OTP remains outside this artifact until the producer exposes the exact authenticated OTP request body; that optional path does not block the eight standard lifecycle packets.",
    "registration_completion targets assigned_cell after the successful RAK. It authenticates the now-registered Noise public key, exact final devId, and current assignment/cell fence. The REG-consumed ticket is intentionally absent from completion.",
    "The completion request carries an SDK-generated synthetic device_api_key candidate. The SDK MUST durably persist the candidate before its first send. The service atomically stores its hash plus an issued sentinel; retrying with the same candidate returns the same device_api_key_id, while a different candidate conflicts.",
    "The completion result list contains exactly query, version, and device_api_key_id; it carries no agent metadata, device_api_key secret, secret-derived hash, or candidate commitment. Assignment results never echo the initial credential. Consumers must explicitly assert both non-echo properties.",
    "The public initial-assignment registration.key_kind vocabulary is exactly bootstrap, connector_bootstrap, account, and agent. tunnel_bootstrap is a private control-plane key_type and MUST NOT cross the LRT wire.",
    "request_cases and success_result_cases are authenticated application-body trust-boundary tests. Producers feed each exact body_json through the same duplicate-aware, exact-case-key, unknown-field-rejecting parser and typed semantic validator used in production; they must derive owner, agent public key, assigned cell, and endpoint only from authenticated server state, never client-supplied placement fields.",
    "Reject classes are consumer-neutral: body_parse covers invalid, duplicate-key, or trailing JSON; unknown_field covers any non-contract or wrong-case key; missing_field covers an absent required key; wrong_type covers a non-object or typed-field mismatch; semantic covers a structurally valid but disallowed value; list_on_error forbids list on an error result; retry_after_missing, retry_after_invalid, and retry_after_unexpected enforce retryAfterSeconds policy; unknown_error_code rejects any unreserved code.",
    "list_on_error applies to NHP_LRT, whose success grammar owns list but error results must omit it. NHP_RAK has no list field in either success or error grammar, so a RAK list is classified as unknown_field instead.",
    "error_contract is application-layer behavioral data pinned to the merged production NHP common-wire revision that reserves these codes and emits retryAfterSeconds. Consumers feed every body_json through the same strict parser and typed classifier used in production, rather than trusting outcome. Errors omit list; unknown codes reject; errMsg is diagnostic only; retryAfterSeconds is optional only for 52200/52300, required for 52204, forbidden elsewhere, and positive when present.",
    "Tickets, identifiers, credentials, keys, hosts, timestamps, and error messages in this artifact are synthetic conformance values. The lv_live_conformance_* strings deliberately retain production credential grammar while the conformance infix makes them non-secret fixtures; downstream scanners may allowlist those exact fixture values. Ticket strings are opaque test data and do not prescribe a ticket encoding."
  ],
